NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now, let's discuss Hope's 1N bid. Given our agreement, it is certainly reasonable. However, I recommend the sandwich NT instead. It is rare when both opponents bid that you have a strong NT. And even if you do, it is very likely partner does not have much. So, playing 1N as natural after both opponents have bid is not really all that useful. Instead, you can play the "sandwich NT." If you play that it shows the other 2 suits, and differs from a takeout double as it tends to show a weaker hand and it tends to emphasize the unbid minor rather than major. In this case, there were 2 unbid minors so that would not apply. |
PG| ***** 131 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|But, if for example, the auction went 1D-P-1H-1N, that would show less than an opening hand with clubs and spades. No more than 4 spades and would say all things being equal, you prefer clubs, often you would have 5, although not guaranteed. However, the sandwich NT rarely comes up, so I just was telling you about it as a point of interest.|
